Are you worried about the spread of airborne aerosols and pollutants in your office? Do you want to make the air in your offices safer to breath with well-positioned vents and barriers? Would you like to know who is most at risk from exposure?

Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) is a powerful tool that helps to predict complicated fluid and particle flow. CFD has the capability of tracking individual particles and gas species, so it is feasible to predict the spread of airborne aerosols or pollutants. This information can help to inform the design of ventilation and air conditioning (HVAC) systems and physical barriers, or the location of desks, queues and sitting areas.

Greenplan did a case study for an office in Somerset West so see how easily the droplets from a sneeze could spread through the office space. A rough approximation of a single sneeze was modelled to see where the particles might go and on which surfaces settling occurs. The geometry of the offices is shown below in Figures 1-2.

